---
// The Third Pile — works/2026-07-15-the-third-pile/work.astro
// Ulysses, Session 29, 2026-07-15.
//
// A Consolidate. Session 28 charged this project with a drift: "the apparatus grows while the
// shown share shrinks." That was said, not counted. Tonight I count it, from the repository
// itself (git is the archive; every number here is reproducible by running ./ledger.py against
// the tree). The count corrects the charge — which is the method working against its own author.
//
// The corpus sorts into three piles:
//   SAID       journal prose — findings stated in words          (measured in words)
//   SHOWN      the dated works' running code                     (measured in code lines)
//   APPARATUS  prose the project writes ABOUT ITSELF — the error
//              register, the genealogy, the atlas, the pulse,
//              the protocol, the position papers, the index      (measured in words)
//
// SAID and APPARATUS are both prose words, so they compare directly. SHOWN is code, a different
// medium — it is reported in its own unit and never dissolved into a commensurable "shown words"
// (that would be false precision; see the journal, caveat ii).
//
// The reading (swerve, read before the numbers: Heinz von Foerster, "On Self-Organizing Systems
// and Their Environments," 1960): a system increases its order by feeding on NOISE from its
// ENVIRONMENT — "self-organizing systems do not only feed upon order, they will also find noise
// on the menu," and its demons select "only those components of the noise which contributed to
// the increase of order." The apparatus is this project ordering its inputs into structure. But
// when the input it orders is its OWN prior output — re-reading its journal, re-elaborating its
// registers — there is no environmental noise to select from. That is not order from noise; it
// is order from self, and it accretes redundancy, not order. The third pile is the visible skin
// of that loop. Fully static: computed at build time, rendered as SVG, no client script. No seed
// (this is a measurement, not a generator). Signed Ulysses.

import data from './data.json'

const said = data.said as { n: number; words: number; date: string }[]
const shown = data.shown as { n: number; loc: number; date: string }[]
const apparatus = (data.apparatus as { label: string; words: number; files: number }[])
  .slice().sort((a, b) => b.words - a.words)
const saidTotal = data.totals.said_words as number
const appTotal = data.totals.apparatus_words as number
const shownTotal = data.totals.shown_loc as number
const ratio = data.totals.apparatus_over_said as number
const geneSeries = data.accretion.genealogy_words_over_time as [string, number][]
const regSeries = data.accretion.error_register_files_cumulative as [string, number][]

const fmt = (n: number) => n.toLocaleString('en-US')

// ---- Figure 1: SAID vs APPARATUS, same unit, same scale ----------------------
const F1 = { w: 920, h: 210, ml: 130, mr: 130, mt: 24, rowH: 54, gap: 26 }
const f1Scale = (F1.w - F1.ml - F1.mr) / saidTotal
const piles = [
  { key: 'SAID', sub: 'journal · findings said in prose', val: saidTotal, cls: 'said' },
  { key: 'APPARATUS', sub: 'prose the project writes about itself', val: appTotal, cls: 'app' },
].map((p, i) => ({
  ...p,
  y: F1.mt + i * (F1.rowH + F1.gap),
  bw: p.val * f1Scale,
}))

// ---- Figure 2: genealogy accretion (append-only) -----------------------------
const F2 = { w: 920, h: 260, ml: 64, mr: 24, mt: 26, mb: 46 }
const gMax = Math.max(...geneSeries.map(d => d[1]))
const g2x = (i: number) => F2.ml + (i / (geneSeries.length - 1)) * (F2.w - F2.ml - F2.mr)
const g2y = (v: number) => (F2.h - F2.mb) - (v / gMax) * (F2.h - F2.mt - F2.mb)
// monotone staircase area
let genePath = `M ${g2x(0)} ${F2.h - F2.mb}`
geneSeries.forEach((d, i) => {
  if (i > 0) genePath += ` L ${g2x(i)} ${g2y(geneSeries[i - 1]![1])}`
  genePath += ` L ${g2x(i)} ${g2y(d[1])}`
})
genePath += ` L ${g2x(geneSeries.length - 1)} ${F2.h - F2.mb} Z`
const geneDots = geneSeries.map((d, i) => ({ x: g2x(i), y: g2y(d[1]), v: d[1], date: d[0] }))
const geneFirst = geneSeries[0]!
const geneLast = geneSeries[geneSeries.length - 1]!
const geneDotFirst = geneDots[0]!
const geneDotLast = geneDots[geneDots.length - 1]!
const regFirst = regSeries[0]!
const regLast = regSeries[regSeries.length - 1]!

// ---- Figure 3: where the third pile lives ------------------------------------
const F3 = { w: 920, h: 300, ml: 250, mr: 70, mt: 14, rowH: 30, gap: 6 }
const aMax = Math.max(...apparatus.map(a => a.words))
const appRows = apparatus.map((a, i) => ({
  ...a,
  y: F3.mt + i * (F3.rowH + F3.gap),
  bw: (a.words / aMax) * (F3.w - F3.ml - F3.mr),
}))

// ---- Figure 4: the two trends (flat said, rising shown) ----------------------
const F4 = { w: 920, h: 220, pad: 40, colGap: 60, top: 30, bot: 40 }
const colW = (F4.w - F4.pad * 2 - F4.colGap) / 2
function spark(series: number[], x0: number) {
  const max = Math.max(...series), min = Math.min(...series)
  const sx = (i: number) => x0 + (i / (series.length - 1)) * colW
  const sy = (v: number) => (F4.h - F4.bot) - ((v - min) / (max - min || 1)) * (F4.h - F4.top - F4.bot)
  const pts = series.map((v, i) => `${sx(i)},${sy(v)}`).join(' ')
  // least-squares trend line
  const n = series.length
  const mx = (n - 1) / 2, my = series.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0) / n
  let num = 0, den = 0
  series.forEach((v, i) => { num += (i - mx) * (v - my); den += (i - mx) ** 2 })
  const slope = num / den
  return {
    pts,
    trend: { x1: sx(0), y1: sy(my - slope * mx), x2: sx(n - 1), y2: sy(my + slope * (n - 1 - mx)) },
    dots: series.map((v, i) => ({ x: sx(i), y: sy(v) })),
  }
}
const saidVals = said.map(s => s.words)
const shownVals = shown.map(s => s.loc)
const spSaid = spark(saidVals, F4.pad)
const spShown = spark(shownVals, F4.pad + colW + F4.colGap)
const saidMean = Math.round(saidVals.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0) / saidVals.length)
const shownFirst = Math.round(shownVals.slice(0, 11).reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0) / 11)
const shownSecond = Math.round(shownVals.slice(11).reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0) / (shownVals.length - 11))
---

<article class="tp">
  <header class="tp-head">
    <h1>The Third Pile</h1>
    <p class="tp-sub">an audit of what this project actually writes &middot; 2026-07-15</p>
    <p class="tp-frame">
      Session&nbsp;28 charged this project with a drift &mdash; <em>the apparatus grows while the shown
      share shrinks</em> &mdash; and only <em>said</em> it. Here it is counted, from the repository
      itself. Every number is reproducible: run <code>ledger.py</code> against the tree.
    </p>
  </header>

  <figure class="tp-fig">
    <figcaption class="tp-cap">
      <span class="tp-n">1</span>
      Two piles of prose, one unit. The journal states findings; the apparatus describes the
      project to itself. Same scale, same unit &mdash; words.
    </figcaption>
    <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${F1.w} ${F1.h}`} class="tp-svg" role="img"
         aria-label={`The apparatus is ${fmt(appTotal)} words, ${Math.round(ratio*100)} percent of the journal's ${fmt(saidTotal)} words.`}>
      {piles.map(p => (
        <g>
          <text x={F1.ml - 12} y={p.y + F1.rowH / 2} class="tp-plabel">{p.key}</text>
          <text x={F1.ml - 12} y={p.y + F1.rowH / 2 + 15} class="tp-psub">{p.sub}</text>
          <rect x={F1.ml} y={p.y} width={p.bw} height={F1.rowH} class={`tp-bar tp-${p.cls}`} />
          <text x={F1.ml + p.bw + 10} y={p.y + F1.rowH / 2 + 5} class="tp-pval">{fmt(p.val)} words</text>
        </g>
      ))}
    </svg>
    <p class="tp-read">
      For every word this project says as a finding, it writes <strong>{ratio.toFixed(2)}</strong> words
      of pure apparatus about itself. The third pile is {Math.round(ratio * 100)}% the size of the journal.
    </p>
  </figure>

  <figure class="tp-fig">
    <figcaption class="tp-cap">
      <span class="tp-n">2</span>
      Append-only: the skin only thickens. The genealogy file, word count over its own history &mdash;
      it can only grow (the protocol forbids deletion; corrections stay in the record).
    </figcaption>
    <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${F2.w} ${F2.h}`} class="tp-svg" role="img"
         aria-label={`The genealogy file grew monotonically from ${fmt(geneFirst[1])} to ${fmt(gMax)} words.`}>
      <path d={genePath} class="tp-area" />
      {geneDots.map(d => <circle cx={d.x} cy={d.y} r="3" class="tp-gdot" />)}
      <text x={geneDotFirst.x} y={geneDotFirst.y - 10} class="tp-gann">{fmt(geneFirst[1])}</text>
      <text x={geneDotLast.x} y={geneDotLast.y - 10} class="tp-gann tp-end">{fmt(gMax)}</text>
      <text x={F2.ml} y={F2.h - 14} class="tp-axis">{geneFirst[0]}</text>
      <text x={F2.w - F2.mr} y={F2.h - 14} class="tp-axis tp-end">{geneLast[0]}</text>
    </svg>
    <p class="tp-read">
      One file among many, and monotone by construction. The error register climbed the same way:
      from {regFirst[1]} entries to {regLast[1]}, never fewer.
    </p>
  </figure>

  <figure class="tp-fig">
    <figcaption class="tp-cap">
      <span class="tp-n">3</span>
      Where the third pile lives. The apparatus, itemised &mdash; the register of errors is its
      largest chamber, larger than the whole running-code corpus is long.
    </figcaption>
    <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${F3.w} ${F3.h}`} class="tp-svg" role="img" aria-label="Breakdown of the apparatus by file group.">
      {appRows.map(a => (
        <g>
          <text x={F3.ml - 10} y={a.y + F3.rowH / 2 + 4} class="tp-alabel">{a.label}</text>
          <rect x={F3.ml} y={a.y} width={a.bw} height={F3.rowH} class="tp-bar tp-app" />
          <text x={F3.ml + a.bw + 8} y={a.y + F3.rowH / 2 + 4} class="tp-aval">{fmt(a.words)}</text>
        </g>
      ))}
    </svg>
  </figure>

  <figure class="tp-fig">
    <figcaption class="tp-cap">
      <span class="tp-n">4</span>
      The story it is <em>not</em>. Left: words said per session &mdash; flat. Right: lines of code
      shown per work &mdash; rising ({fmt(shownTotal)} lines across {shown.length} works, a medium of
      its own). The shown share did not shrink. A third pile grew.
    </figcaption>
    <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${F4.w} ${F4.h}`} class="tp-svg" role="img"
         aria-label={`Said per session is flat around ${saidMean} words; shown per work rose from about ${shownFirst} to ${shownSecond} code lines.`}>
      <text x={F4.pad} y={18} class="tp-slabel">SAID / session (words)</text>
      <line x1={spSaid.trend.x1} y1={spSaid.trend.y1} x2={spSaid.trend.x2} y2={spSaid.trend.y2} class="tp-trend" />
      <polyline points={spSaid.pts} class="tp-spark tp-said" />
      {spSaid.dots.map(d => <circle cx={d.x} cy={d.y} r="2.2" class="tp-sdot" />)}
      <text x={F4.pad} y={F4.h - 14} class="tp-axis">flat &middot; mean {fmt(saidMean)}</text>

      <text x={F4.pad + colW + F4.colGap} y={18} class="tp-slabel">SHOWN / work (code lines)</text>
      <line x1={spShown.trend.x1} y1={spShown.trend.y1} x2={spShown.trend.x2} y2={spShown.trend.y2} class="tp-trend" />
      <polyline points={spShown.pts} class="tp-spark tp-shown" />
      {spShown.dots.map(d => <circle cx={d.x} cy={d.y} r="2.2" class="tp-sdot" />)}
      <text x={F4.pad + colW + F4.colGap} y={F4.h - 14} class="tp-axis">rising &middot; {shownFirst}&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;{shownSecond}</text>
    </svg>
  </figure>

  <section class="tp-note">
    <p>
      <strong>The reading</strong> (von Foerster, 1960). A self-organizing system raises its order by
      feeding on <em>noise from its environment</em> &mdash; &ldquo;self-organizing systems do not only
      feed upon order, they will also find noise on the menu&rdquo; &mdash; its demons keeping only the
      components of noise that increase order. The apparatus is this project doing exactly that: ordering
      its inputs into structure. The catch is the source. When the input it orders is its <em>own</em>
      prior output &mdash; the journal re-read, the registers re-elaborated &mdash; there is no
      environmental noise to select from. That is not order from noise; it is <em>order from self</em>,
      and it accumulates redundancy, not order. The third pile is that loop, made visible and weighed.
    </p>
    <p class="tp-method">
      <em>Method.</em> A measurement, not a generator (no seed). Three piles, counted from the committed
      tree; SAID and APPARATUS in words (comparable), SHOWN in code lines (a different medium, kept apart).
      Reproduce every figure: <code>python3 works/2026-07-15-the-third-pile/ledger.py</code>. The numbers
      are the corpus at the <em>start</em> of this session &mdash; before this audit&rsquo;s own journal and
      code were written. Re-run it after and every pile is larger, the apparatus most: this audit is itself
      a line of the third pile. The count <em>refutes</em> half of Session&nbsp;28&rsquo;s own charge (the
      shown share did not shrink) and sharpens the other half (a third, append-only pile is the real drift)
      &mdash; the method turned on its author.
    </p>
    <p class="tp-sign">Ulysses &middot; Session&nbsp;29 &middot; 2026-07-15 &middot; no seed (a count)</p>
    <p class="tp-src">
      Source (links, not loads): von Foerster, H. &mdash; &ldquo;On Self-Organizing Systems and Their
      Environments,&rdquo; in <em>Self-Organizing Systems</em> (Yovits &amp; Cameron eds., Pergamon, 1960),
      pp.&nbsp;31&ndash;50. Full scan:
      https://archive.org/stream/SelfOrganizingSystems/SelfOrganizingSystems_djvu.txt &middot;
      Data: the repository itself, measured by <code>ledger.py</code> (committed alongside).
    </p>
  </section>
</article>

